passages.text: We update our model following Eiffage's H1 results (link to our first take). Our 25E EBIT decreases slightly as we increase our estimate for the Holding level loss, with our Contracting EBIT increasing and Concessions EBIT very slightly decreasing. We also incorporate revised guidance for the impact of France's surtax in 2025, underpinning the increase in our 25E Net Income. Our Dec- 26 PT is unchanged at €136, now implying \(25\%\) upside to the current share price, despite our increased estimates as we MTM in our WACC for interest rates.

Eiffage is a leading company in the European concessions and public works sector, operating through four business lines: concessions, construction, infrastructure, energy. While we have previously acknowledged the lower- than- average concession duration, which remains an overhang on re- rating, we see valuation support driven by a number of positives, including: (i) toll road traffic above 2019 levels which should remain resilient despite downturn; (ii) limited airport exposure; (iii) all- time high order book which should provide good revenue visibility going into a weaker macroeconomic environment, as well as margins which should also remain resilient; (iv) a strong balance sheet; and (v) a potential motorway concession extension.

We value the Group on a SOTP basis and use a \(7.98\%\) WACC assumption for the valuation of the toll roads division. We use 2026E EV/EBIT multiples of c.7x to value the contracting divisions of Eiffage (on average).
We update our model post HY25 results and detail the estimate changes below.

**Contracting.** Our revenue estimates increase as we revise our H2 activity expectations upwards for Construction and Infrastructure in response to strong activity levels in H1, with base effects increasing our 26/27E. At the EBIT level we tweak our 2025 margin assumptions, which we slightly raise for Energy and Infrastructure. Overall, our 25E Contracting EBIT increases 2.8%.

**Concessions.** We adjust our APRR traffic forecasts, which decrease for HV but rise for LV, and raise our assumptions for tariff and mix effects. We also reduce our revenue expectations for other concessions.

**Holding.** Our estimates for the holding loss increase in response to reported H1: we look for H2 flat y/y. This is the driver of the overall decrease in our 2025E EBIT,while our 26/27E EBIT rises as a result of our improved operational outlook.

**Net Income.** We incorporate new guidance for the impact of France's surtax,underpinning our higher 2025 Net Income. We now look for an impact of c.£200m in 2025, offset by a c.£70m decrease in Net Income attributable to minorities, with an overall effect on Attributable Net Income of £130m. We have also reduced our expectations for the underlying ETR (ex surtax), where we now model a full year number equal to that reported in H1.
